04273nam a22006615i 9780292759275DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212014txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927592757 a10.7560/7592682doi  a(DE-B1597)587051  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPOL0570002bisacsh04a364.13109822231 aWright, Thomas C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImpunity, Human Rights, and Democracy :bChile and Argentina, 1990-2005 /cThomas C. Wright. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Acronyms -- tIntroduction -- t1. State Terrorism in the Southern Cone -- t2. The Construction of Impunity -- t3. Human Rights Advocacy -- t4. The Changing Legal Environment, Domestic and International -- t5. Precipitating Events -- t6. The Eclipse of Impunity -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUniversal human rights standards were adopted in 1948, but in the 1970s and 1980s, violent dictatorships in Argentina and Chile flagrantly defied the new protocols. Chilean general Augusto Pinochet and the Argentine military employed state terrorism in their quest to eradicate Marxism and other forms of “subversion.” Pinochet constructed an iron shield of impunity for himself and the military in Chile, while in Argentina, military pressure resulted in laws preventing prosecution for past human rights violations. When democracy was reestablished in both countries by 1990, justice for crimes against humanity seemed beyond reach. Thomas C. Wright examines how persistent advocacy by domestic and international human rights groups, evolving legal environments, unanticipated events that impacted public opinion, and eventual changes in military leadership led to a situation unique in the world—the stripping of impunity not only from a select number of commanders of the repression but from all those involved in state terrorism in Chile and Argentina. This has resulted in trials conducted by national courts, without United Nations or executive branch direction, in which hundreds of former repressors have been convicted and many more are indicted or undergoing trial. Impunity, Human Rights, and Democracy draws on extensive research, including interviews, to trace the erosion and collapse of the former repressors’ impunity—a triumph for human rights advocates that has begun to inspire authorities in other Latin American countries, including Peru, Uruguay, Brazil, and Guatemala, to investigate past human rights violations and prosecute their perpetrators.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aDemocracyzArgentina. 0aDemocracyzChile. 0aHuman rightszArgentina. 0aHuman rightszChile. 0aImpunityzArgentina. 0aImpunityzChile. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75926840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292759275423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292759275/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK